sources.title: Articles on Smashing Magazine — For Web Designers And Developers

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Victor Yocco & Dana Daniels)
articles.description: Product teams benefit from knowing their users’ needs and how they respond to product updates as they build out the roadmap of a product. This article covers Voice of Customer programs and is aimed at those who work on a product team as well as executives who are looking for how to better inform your products using insight from users.
articles.title: Creating And Maintaining A Voice Of Customer Program

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Matthew Mattei)
articles.description: Effective collaboration between designers and developers is vital to creating good user experiences. However, bridging the handoff between design and development with the many tools and workflows available today has its pitfalls. Matthew Mattei introduces you to the Uno Platform, which offers a robust set of productivity boosters.
articles.title: An Efficient Design-to-Code Handoff Process Using Uno Platform For Figma

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Temani Afif)
articles.description: Ribbons have been used to accent designs for many years now. But, the way we approach them in CSS has evolved with the introduction of newer features. In this article, Temani Afif combines background and gradient tricks to create ribbon shapes in CSS that are not only responsive but support multi-line text and are easily adjustable with a few CSS variables.
articles.title: CSS Responsive Multi-Line Ribbon Shapes (Part 1)

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Frederick O’Brien)
articles.description: Words alone aren’t enough to safeguard best practices in the world of web design and development. Web design documentation must be like its medium — interactive and constantly evolving.
articles.title: Designing Web Design Documentation

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Oriana García)
articles.description: Animation and accessibility are often seen as two separate powers at odds with one another. How is it possible to strike a balance between elements that move and the possible negative effects they expose to users who are sensitive to motion? Oriana García explains how her team at Mercado Libre tackled the challenge by creating guiding principles for applying animation to user interfaces and incorporating them into the team’s design system.
articles.title: Creating Accessible UI Animations

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Ganesh Dahal)
articles.description: WordPress Playground began as an experiment to see what a self-hosted WordPress experience might look like without the requirement of having to actually install WordPress. A year later, the experiment has evolved into a full-fledged project. Ganesh Dahal demonstrates how WordPress Playground works and gets deep into how it might be used.
articles.title: WordPress Playground: From 5-Minute Install To Instant Spin-Up

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Maxwell Barvian)
articles.description: The CSS `clamp()` function is often paired with viewport units for “fluid” font sizing that scales the text up and down at different viewport sizes. As common as this technique is, several voices warn that it opens up situations where text can fail WCAG Success Criterion 1.4.4, which specifies that text should scale up to at least 200% when the user’s browser reaches its 500% maximum zoom level. Max Barvian takes a deep look at the issue and offers ideas to help address it.
articles.title: Addressing Accessibility Concerns With Using Fluid Type

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Preethi Sam)
articles.description: Icons are capable of enhancing the content that surrounds them, but they have to be self-explanatory for that to happen. We have icons for things we like (a thumbs up), things we can share (a box topped with an up arrow), and even for protection against malicious online attacks (a shield), but what are the options we have for representing “privacy”?
articles.title: In Search Of The Ideal Privacy Icon

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Geoff Graham)
articles.description: Take a closer look at how various performance tools audit and report on performance metrics, such as core web vitals. Geoff Graham answers a set of common questions that pop up during performance audits.
articles.title: Answering Common Questions About Interpreting Page Speed Reports

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Cosima Mielke)
articles.description: November is just around the corner, and with it, a new collection of desktop wallpapers to celebrate the beginning of the month. Designed by creatives from all across the globe, they come in versions with and without a calendar. Let’s make this November colorful!
articles.title: Tales Of November (2023 Wallpapers Edition)

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Neal Fennimore)
articles.description: Passkeys are beginning to make their way into popular apps, from password managers to multi-factor authenticators, but what exactly are they? As this new technology promises to make passwords a thing of the past, Neal Fennimore explains the concepts behind passkeys, demonstrates how they work, and speculates what we might expect from them in the future.
articles.title: Passkeys: A No-Frills Explainer On The Future Of Password-Less Authentication

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Victoria Johnson)
articles.description: Victoria Johnson began a career in front-end development upon graduating from college. Now, roughly one year later, she reflects back on the decisions she made to crack into the field and find her first full-time job. This is her story, and she’s sharing it to provide those who are just starting out with another beginner’s perspective.
articles.title: What I Wish I Knew About Working In Development Right Out Of School

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Maximilian Speicher & Johanna Jagow)
articles.description: Inuit (short for “**In**terface **U**sability **I**nstrumen**t**”) is a new questionnaire you can use to assess the usability of your user interface. It has been designed to be more diagnostic than existing usability instruments like, e.g., SUS and for use with machine learning, all the while asking fewer questions than other questionnaires. This article explores how and why Inuit has been developed and why we can be sure that it actually measures usability, and reliably so.
articles.title: An Actionable And Reliable Usability Questionnaire With Only 7 Items: Inuit

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Geoff Graham)
articles.description: Having access to a free reporting tool like Lighthouse in DevTools is a great start for diagnosing performance issues by identifying bottlenecks on the main thread. Even better are paid tools like [SpeedCurve](https://www.speedcurve.com/?utm_source=smashingmag&utm_medium=magazine&utm_campaign=sm7_2023&utm_id=sm7_2023&utm_term=sm7_2023) to dig deeper into the data for more targeted insights and to produce visual reports to help make a case for performance improvements for your team and other stakeholders.
articles.title: The Fight For The Main Thread

articles.author: hello@smashingmagazine.com (Juan Diego Rodríguez)
articles.description: Removing properties from an object in JavaScript might not be the most exciting job, but there are many ways to achieve it, each revealing a fundamental aspect of how JavaScript works. Juan Diego Rodríguez explores each technique in this article.
articles.title: What Removing Object Properties Tells Us About JavaScript

articles.author: Justice Nwogu
articles.description: User authentication is critical to mobile app development. It helps make sure that only authorized users can access sensitive information and perform actions within an application. In this tutorial, we will explore how to build secure user authentication in Flutter using Firebase for authentication and the Bloc state management pattern
articles.title: How to Build a Secure User Authentication Flow in Flutter with Firebase and Bloc State Management

articles.author: Joan Ayebola
articles.description: JavaScript is a powerful and versatile programming language that is widely used for creating dynamic and interactive web pages. articles.title: How to Use If Statements in JavaScript – a Beginner's Guide

articles.description: Today I'm joined by Dr. Curran Kelleher. He's a data visualization expert and has taught a number of in-depth data visualization courses on freeCodeCamp's YouTube channel. articles.author: Hunor Márton Borbély
articles.description: In this tutorial, you'll learn how to create a game that's inspired by Stick Hero – using plain JavaScript and HTML canvas. articles.title: JavaScript Game Tutorial – Build a Stick Hero Clone with HTML Canvas + JavaScript

articles.author: Jess Wilk
articles.description: Have you ever wondered how websites can offer their content in multiple languages, perfectly tailored to different cultures and regions?  Well, that magic is called localization, and it's a game-changer for web development – especially when using Django, a super versatile Python framework.  It's not just about translating
articles.title: How to Localize Your Django App

articles.description: In November of 2022, Artificial Intelligence took center stage in the tech world. articles.title: ChatGPT vs BARD AI – What's the Difference?

articles.author: Okosa Leonard Onyekachukwu
articles.description: React's ecosystem is always growing, and it seems like there are always new features and enhancements to make development more effective and user-friendly.  React Suspense is one such feature that has become quite popular among React devs. In this guide, you'll learn all about React Suspense and examine its
articles.title: How to Use React Suspense to Improve your React Projects

articles.description: You need to prepare if you want to perform well in technical developer job interviews. articles.title: Master Technical Interviews
